+\subsection{Bounded-Domain Curl-Spectrum Benchmarks}
+    \label{subsec:bounded_domain_curl_spectrum}
+
+    \textbf{[ORTHODOX / SPECTRAL BENCHMARK].}
+    Let \(\Omega\subset\mathbb{R}^3\) be a smooth bounded domain and let
+    \(\mathbf{V}\) be divergence-free and tangent to \(\partial\Omega\).  In the
+    bounded-domain curl eigenproblem
+    \begin{align}
+        \nabla\times\mathbf{V}
+        &=
+        \kappa_{\rm curl}\mathbf{V},
+        &
+        \nabla\cdot\mathbf{V}&=0,
+        &
+        \mathbf{V}\cdot\mathbf{n}\big|_{\partial\Omega}&=0,
+        \label{eq:canon_curl_eigenproblem}
+    \end{align}
+    the smallest positive eigenvalue is a property of the complete domain and its
+    boundary conditions, not of the centreline alone
+    \cite{CantarellaDeTurckGluckTeytel2000CurlSpherical}.
+
+    For a ball \(B_b^3\) of radius \(b\),
+    \begin{align}
+        \kappa_1(B_b^3)
+        &=
+        \frac{x_1}{b},
+        &
+        \tan x_1&=x_1,
+        &
+        x_1&=4.493409458\ldots,
+        \label{eq:canon_ball_curl_eigenvalue}
+    \end{align}
+    with multiplicity three.  For a concentric spherical shell
+    \(B^3(a,b)=\{a<r<b\}\), the first positive eigenvalue is the smallest positive
+    root of
+    \begin{align}
+        J_{3/2}(a\kappa)Y_{3/2}(b\kappa)
+        -
+        J_{3/2}(b\kappa)Y_{3/2}(a\kappa)
+        =0.
+        \label{eq:canon_shell_curl_eigenvalue}
+    \end{align}
+
+    In the normalization
+    \begin{align}
+        \mathscr E_V
+        &=
+        \int_\Omega |\mathbf{V}|^2\,d^3x,
+        &
+        \mathscr H_V
+        &=
+        \left\langle
+        \mathbf{V},\operatorname{BS}_{K(\Omega)}\mathbf{V}
+        \right\rangle_{L^2},
+    \end{align}
+    a curl eigenfield satisfies
+    \begin{align}
+        \mathscr E_V
+        =
+        \kappa_{\rm curl}\mathscr H_V,
+        \qquad
+        \frac{\mathscr H_V}{\mathscr E_V}
+        =
+        \frac{1}{\kappa_{\rm curl}}.
+        \label{eq:canon_helicity_capacity_relation}
+    \end{align}
+
+    \textbf{[CANON / SCOPE GUARD].}
+    Equations~\eqref{eq:canon_ball_curl_eigenvalue} and
+    \eqref{eq:canon_shell_curl_eigenvalue} are exact benchmarks only for the stated
+    filled spherical domains.  The constant \(4.493409458\ldots\) is not a universal
+    SST particle constant, the distinguished central orbit of the eigenfield is not
+    an independently resolved vortex core, and neither formula determines
+    \(a_{\rm core}\) or \(r_{\rm horn}\) for a knotted tube.
+
